images.description: NASA Recovery Team Leader Dr. Donald E. Stullken leads Apollo 7 Astronauts Walter M. Schirra, Jr., Donn F. Eisele and Walter Cunningham across flight deck of USS Essex, Prime recovery ship, following the trio's recovery in the Atlantic Ocean.

Apollo 7 Astronauts (l-r) Walter M. Schirra, Jr., Donn F. Eisele and Walter Cunningham pause in doorway of recovery helicopter which carried them from their landing point to the deck of the USS Essex, prime recovery ship.
Apollo 7 astronauts (l-r) Walter M. Schirra, Jr., Donn F. Eisele and Walter Cunningham received a "red carpet welcome" aboard the USS Essex, prime recovery ship.
President Lyndon B. Johnson congratulated the Apollo 7 astronauts (l-r) Donn F. Eisele, Walter M. Schirra, Jr., and Walter Cunningham via ship-to-shore telephone following the space pilots' recovery.
Navy personnel hoist the Apollo 7 spacecraft aboard the USS Essex, prime recovery ship.

Apollo 7 Command Walter M. Schirra, Jr., waves to well-wishers aboard the USS Essex following his recovery with Astronauts Donn F. Eisele, center, and Walter Cunningham at the completion of their 11-day earth orbital mission.
Pararescuemen attach flotation collar to Apollo 7 spacecraft after it splashed down on 10/22/68 in the Atlantic Ocean.
Apollo 7 commander Walter M. Schirra, Jr. is hoisted aboard recovery helicopter after he and Astronauts Donn F. Eisele and Walter Cunningham splashed down in the Atlantic Ocean.

After their 4.5-million-mile space journey, Apollo 7 Astronauts (l-r) Walter Cunningham, Walter M. Schirra, Jr. and Donn Eisele greet well-wishers aboard the USS Essex, prime recovery ship, following their splashdown in the Atlantic Ocean.

Two members of the first three-man Apollo crew scheduled to orbit the earth later this year, view unmanned lunar module launching (Apollo 5) at Cape Kennedy's Complex 37.  Walter Schirra (l) and Walter Cunningham.
